00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.880
But there was never
anyone that made me feel

00:08:27.880 --> 00:08:32.620
like it was something
I shouldn't be doing.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:39.240
They also never made me feel
like I could make a living at it.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:40.540
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: Not many do though.

00:08:40.540 --> 00:08:44.450
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Yeah, so there
was a kind of freedom in that too,

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:51.490
that I just thought oh well
this seems like something to do.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:54.810
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: There's a
painful poem about your mother,

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:56.740
I wonder if you'd read,
called "Late."

00:08:56.740 --> 00:09:01.400
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Okay, okay, yeah
I haven't read that one in a while.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:02.960
"Late" from "Muscular Music."

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:05.430
This late no one is clean.

00:09:05.430 --> 00:09:08.360
Not the bus's worn blue seats,
which keep themselves company.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:11.510
Or the nurse in her
drowsy yellow uniform.

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:15.270
It's February and I
haven't spoken to my mother

00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:18.420
since she told me to
take my shit and go.

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:20.980 position:56%
Her face bare and serious as a wall.

00:09:20.980 --> 00:09:26.140
The driver waves a gloved
hand at a passing bus;

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:27.860
slow and half empty like us.

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:31.710
Heads of the riders turned so
that I cannot say how they appear.

00:09:31.710 --> 00:09:33.010
I was not born in this place.

00:09:33.010 --> 00:09:34.310
But it is where I will try to live.

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:35.610
The miles between my mother and
here, stretching me into more

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:36.910
of a man than my father,
who'd drive from his

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:38.210
out of state job each weekend
to let her break his skin.

00:09:38.210 --> 00:09:39.510
I'm glad I've left her sitting

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:40.810
in that house waiting
for her nails to grow.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:42.110
Once she pulled a gun on me

00:09:42.110 --> 00:09:43.410
because as she told the police
I was too big for a belt.

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:44.710
I called them, but they
did not take her away.

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:46.010
Later my father drove home and
said never put our business

00:09:46.010 --> 00:09:47.310
in the street.

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:48.610
So, I shouldn't be telling you
this, how we sat in that house

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:49.910
like a family while a small
light beat the blinds.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:51.210
My mother stubborn as a girl
who will not comb her hair.

00:09:51.210 --> 00:09:52.510
There is no light beyond
the windows of this bus.

00:09:52.510 --> 00:09:53.810
I am given my face, transparent
and bare on the glass.

00:09:53.810 --> 00:09:55.110
After my father left that
night, the two of us sat apart

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:56.410 position:56%
in the living room as the TV lit the
walls, the old white gown trembling

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:57.710
on her shoulders like
the sings of a moth.

00:09:57.710 --> 00:09:59.010
I will say I did not
know she began to cry.

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:00.310
I was 18, trying to be a man.

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:01.610
It has taken me too
long to say this.

00:10:01.610 --> 00:10:02.910
I am the same thing
I've always been.

00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:04.210
A son. I do not know my mother.

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:05.510
But I want to touch her
now, as I did not then.

00:10:05.510 --> 00:10:06.810
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: Lovely.

00:10:06.810 --> 00:10:08.110
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Thanks.

00:10:08.110 --> 00:10:09.410
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: I shouldn't
be telling you this.

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:10.710
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: You
want me to talk about that?

00:10:10.710 --> 00:10:12.010
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: Yeah, what's
it like to write that sort

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:13.310
of intimate confessing of poetry.

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:16.180
What are the costs of
exposing your own feelings

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:18.420 position:56%
and other people's feelings to that?

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:20.060
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Well the
great thing about my mom,

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:23.870
because she does have a pretty
wild imagination, and you know,

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:28.180
in a different time, maybe like
20 years from now she would,

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:29.480
you know she would be me.

00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:33.550
But she essentially said, you
know it's all your imagination,

00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:35.700
you got such a good imagination.

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.900
So, that was like license
to say whatever.

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:41.370
So, I don't think she ever thinks
of my work as purely confessional,

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:43.430
she thinks that I'm
just making stuff up.

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:45.310
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: Do you think
you're ever confessional?

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:49.440
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Yeah, yeah, but
I think an advantage of poetry is

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:51.510
that you can kind of come
in and out of metaphor

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:53.680
and in and out of shadow.

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:55.940
So, I can sort of be confessional

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:59.000
when people think I'm
not being confessional,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.250
and you know dress things

00:11:01.250 --> 00:11:03.240
when I don't want them
to be so confessional.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:04.950
I mean what she said
about that poem is that,

00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:06.250
well I never pointed it at you.

00:11:06.250 --> 00:11:07.550
She was like [laughter].

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:08.850
I showed you the gun.

00:11:08.850 --> 00:11:11.690
And said, I can see how that
would be good for drama.

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:14.400
But you know she actually
did have it out, so.

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:15.700
&gt;&gt; RON CHARLES: In
another poem, you said,

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.530
I knew later I'd be writing
these lines caught in that space

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:20.390
between personal and public.

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:22.340
What is that space between
personal and public?

00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:23.640
How do you negotiate that?

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:25.210
How do you preserve that as a poet,

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:26.810
who wants to write
about his own life?

00:11:26.810 --> 00:11:29.660
&gt;&gt; TERRANCE HAYES: Sure, yeah, well
I mean even the word that shows

00:11:29.660 --> 00:11:32.740
up in that poem, transparency
that shows

00:11:32.740 --> 00:11:36.140
up in the last poem is really
what I'm trying to achieve,

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:40.180
a certain kind of clarity, both
in the language and in feeling.

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:46.360 position:56%
So, my sense is that if you can get
it right, if you can get the rhythm,

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:49.120
and the language, and
the sensibility right,

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:51.980
you can say whatever
you want to say.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:55.610
Anything can be said if you
can say it right and sometimes

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:57.850
that means beautifully,
sometimes that means rawly.

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:00.210 position:56%
Sometimes that means metaphorically.

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:03.220
So, whatever you think of as
right is what I'm always sort

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:04.520
of going for.

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:07.530
And when there's a failure
there, if someone says, you know,

00:12:07.530 --> 00:12:09.710
if my mother, and they haven't
said it yet, nor my father,

00:12:09.710 --> 00:12:15.110 position:56%
